- Change storage key to `"t3code:theme:v2"` (new format). Add migration: read old `"t3code:theme"` and map `"dark"` → `"t3-dark"`, `"light"` → `"t3-light"`, `"system"` → `"t3-dark"` (or detect system preference)
- `getStored()` now returns a theme ID string (default: `DEFAULT_THEME_ID`)
- `applyTheme()` now:
  1. Looks up the `ThemeDefinition` via `getTheme(id)`
  2. Toggles `.dark` class based on `theme.appearance`
  3. Sets CSS custom properties on `document.documentElement.style`:
     - `--background` ← `theme.colors.background`
     - `--foreground` ← `theme.colors.foreground`
     - `--accent` / `--accent-foreground` ← `theme.colors.accent`
     - `--primary` / `--ring` ← `theme.colors.accent`
     - `--sidebar` ← `theme.colors.sidebar` (new variable)
     - `--editor` ← `theme.colors.editor` (new variable)
     - `--terminal` ← `theme.colors.terminal` (new variable)
     - `--status-bar` ← `theme.colors.statusBar` (new variable)
     - `--font-family` ← `theme.fontFamily` (new variable)
     - `--font-size` ← `theme.fontSize + "px"` (new variable)
  4. Suppresses transitions during changes (keep existing pattern)
- **Return type extended** (backward-compatible):
  ```ts
  {
    theme: ThemeDefinition;        // full theme object (NEW)
    setTheme: (id: string) => void; // accepts theme ID (signature change but same pattern)
    resolvedTheme: "light" | "dark"; // PRESERVED — derived from theme.appearance
    availableThemes: readonly ThemeDefinition[]; // NEW
  }
  ```

**Migration note:** The existing `setTheme("light" | "dark" | "system")` callers in `_chat.settings.tsx` will be updated to pass theme IDs instead.

### 4. `apps/web/src/index.css` — Add new CSS variable fallbacks

In both `:root` and `@variant dark` blocks, add fallback definitions for the new variables so components work even before JS applies theme overrides:
```css
/* In :root (light) */
--sidebar: var(--color-neutral-50);
--editor: var(--color-white);
--terminal: var(--color-white);
--status-bar: var(--color-neutral-100);

/* In @variant dark */
--sidebar: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-neutral-950) 90%, var(--color-white));
--editor: var(--background);
--terminal: var(--color-neutral-950);
--status-bar: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-neutral-950) 85%, var(--color-white));
```

Also add to `@theme inline`:
```css
--color-sidebar: var(--sidebar);
--color-editor: var(--editor);
--color-terminal: var(--terminal);
--color-status-bar: var(--status-bar);
```

Update the `body` font-family to reference a CSS variable with fallback:
```css
body {
  font-family: var(--font-family, "DM Sans", -apple-system, ...);
  font-size: var(--font-size, inherit);
}
```

### 5. `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx` — New theme selector component

A standalone component that renders available themes as selectable cards with color preview swatches. Follow existing component patterns (functional component, Tailwind classes, semantic color tokens).

**Structure:**
```tsx
export function ThemeSelector() {
  const { theme, setTheme, availableThemes } = useTheme();

  return (
    <div role="radiogroup" aria-label="Theme">
      {availableThemes.map((t) => (
        <button role="radio" aria-checked={theme.id === t.id} onClick={() => setTheme(t.id)}>
          {/* Theme name */}
          {/* Color swatch row: 4-5 small colored circles showing
              background, foreground, accent, sidebar, editor */}
          {/* Selected badge (matching existing settings pattern) */}
        </button>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

**Swatch design:** A row of small colored circles (12x12 or 16x16) showing key theme colors. This gives users an instant visual preview. Follow the same card/button pattern used in the existing settings theme radio buttons.

### 6. `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.settings.tsx` — Update Appearance section

Replace the existing `THEME_OPTIONS` radio group with the new `<ThemeSelector />` component.

**Changes:**
- Remove the hardcoded `THEME_OPTIONS` array
- Import and render `<ThemeSelector />` inside the Appearance `<section>`
- Keep the "Active theme" display but reference `theme.name` instead of `resolvedTheme`
- Remove the old `theme`/`setTheme` destructuring; use the new `useTheme()` return shape

